HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 983
By Faison
A RESOLUTION to commend Representative Monty Fritts for his
honorable and astute service to the people of
Tennessee as a member of the House of
Representatives.
WHEREAS, it is most appropriate that the members of this General Assembly should
honor those fellow legislators who have performed their duties with the utmost integrity and
whose efforts during their time in office have been dedicated to providing thoughtful and
exemplary service to their districts and to this great State; and
WHEREAS, Representative Monty Fritts of Kingston is one such distinguished public
servant, who has served both his constituency and this legislative body with honor and ability;
and
WHEREAS, during his tenure, Representative Fritts has been a highly influential figure
in the political, social, and civic life of Roane and Loudon counties, and he has served his
constituents in numerous capacities, always working diligently at his elected duties and
expending the necessary effort to understand the opposing sides of complex issues; and
WHEREAS, Monty Fritts has distinguished himself as a public-spirited citizen of the
highest order and as an exceptional asset to the good people of the 32nd House District, whom
he has served as a member of the 113th and 114th General Assemblies; and
WHEREAS, throughout his service, Monty Fritts has been prominent as a dedicated and
well-informed legislator who always votes his conscience; and
WHEREAS, Representative Fritts earned his Bachelor of Science and Master of Arts
degrees from Liberty University and holds a Master of Business Administration degree from the
University of Tennessee; he also completed a certificate program in Leading Operations
Excellence through the Massachusetts Institute of Technology; and
HJR0983
012807
- 1 -

WHEREAS, although he is now a realtor, Monty Fritts spent most of his career in nuclear
manufacturing; and
WHEREAS, starting as an hourly employee, he progressed into management and held
positions as an Operations Manager in foreign nuclear non-proliferation efforts, Director-
Manager of Enriched Uranium Operations, Program Liaison to NNSA, and University of
Tennessee, Knoxville, Leadership Development Liaison at the Y-12 National Security Complex;
and
WHEREAS, he also served as Director of Operations at Nuclear Fuel Services in Erwin,
held a position at the U.S. Department of Energy, and was a Vice-President of Business
Development; and
WHEREAS, he received letters of appreciation from U.S. Secretary of Defense Gates
and U.S. Secretary of Energy Bodman in recognition of his many contributions; and
WHEREAS, a proud veteran, Representative Fritts initially served his country in the U.S.
Army from 1983 until 1993; he then reenlisted in 2003 to support the 278 Armored Cavalry
Regiment's deployment to Iraq; and
WHEREAS, during his exemplary military career, he earned the Army Combat Action
Badge, two Army Commendations, the Good Conduct Medal, several campaign medals while
serving in a combat zone, two Overseas Deployment Bars, the Army Achievement RC, NCO
Professional Development ribbons, and combat service patches with the 1st Infantry Division,
the 42nd Infantry Division, and the 278 Regimental Combat Team; and
WHEREAS, an active and dynamic participant in the legislative process during his time
in the General Assembly, Representative Monty Fritts has rendered sterling service as Co-Chair
of the Veterans Caucus, Vice-Chair of the Naming and Designating Committee, and Vice-Chair
of the Joint Government Operations Education, Health and General Welfare Subcommittee; and
- 2 - 012807

WHEREAS, he has also served with distinction as a member of the Agriculture and
Natural Resources Committee, Government Operations Committee, Agriculture and Natural
Resources Subcommittee, Joint Government Operations Commerce, Labor, Transportation and
Agriculture Subcommittee, and the Joint Government Operations Judiciary and Government
Subcommittee; and
WHEREAS, he further served on the Nuclear Legislative Working Group within the
National Conference of State Legislatures, the Southern States Energy Board, and the Energy
and Environment Committee of the Council of State Governments; and
WHEREAS, Monty Fritts has proven that citizens can make a difference by being
involved in their community, which he has demonstrated as a life member of the VFW (Post
5150 Loudon), the American Legion (Post 50 Rockwood), the National Rifle Association, The
Society of the First Infantry Division, and the Tennessee Firearms Association and a member of
the Gun Owners of America and the National Association of Gun Rights; and
WHEREAS, he is an ardent supporter of the Life Choices Medical Center and the Parent
Loss Scholarship Fund at Liberty University; and
WHEREAS, a member of First Baptist Church Rockwood, Representative Fritts is most
grateful for the love and companionship he shares with his wife, Denise, their two sons and
daughters-in-law, and their three grandchildren; and
WHEREAS, throughout his outstanding career as a public servant, Representative Fritts
has worked tirelessly on behalf of his constituents, bringing to his office an honorable bearing
and the traditional values of hard work and common sense; and
WHEREAS, Representative Monty Fritts is wholly committed to the noble precepts of
public service that have earned Tennessee recognition as the Volunteer State, and he should
be specially recognized for his exemplary tenure in the General Assembly; now, therefore,
- 3 - 012807

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we hereby honor Representative Monty Fritts for his meritorious service to
Tennessee as a member of the House of Representatives, commend him for his countless
contributions and many good works in service of the citizens of the 32nd House District, and
extend to him our best wishes for much continued success and happiness.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
- 4 - 012807

